text: You have hit on exactly the source of, I'm not going to say our biggest dilemma, but it is our biggest kind of, time sucks, also not the right word, but it's the biggest kind of thrust of this business is managing the expectations, even managing their own risk tolerance. I mean, one thing we've started toying around with in a very simple, you've written about this extensively, and I think it adds a lot of merit to this process is kind of asking questions at the forefront of the investor, even simple questions like, not the kind of conamon, if I give you two different coin flips and one had a 78% chance and dah, dah, dah, but even more simple than that and just saying, for this index, would you, and you've got to be careful here, I'm going to caveat it. You obviously, you don't want to lead them into a data mining exercise, but- And it's been helpful for us to help understand how they think about their own objective function because humans are phenomenal liars to themselves. So we'll ask the question, 2008 versus 2013, as an example. 2013, the S&P was way up. 2008, the S&P was way down. What would be your preferences for whatever, a tactical sector product in those years? Because there's a lot of different implementations, all of which are robust and built with integrity, but they have different risk, maybe they may not have the same Sharpe ratio, but they have different characteristics from year to year. And like it or not, that matters for a lot of these guys. And so, would you be okay being flat in 2008, arguably with 30% alpha, but only being up 1% in 2013 when the S&P was ripping? And almost invariably, what we find anyway is people are, at least the folks we're talking to, they're much more in index hugging mode. I say index broad-based index hugging mode than they would like to admit or probably even realize. And so, a lot of it, I don't have a good answer for you, but a lot of it is just kind of poking at the, trying to triangulate in on to what degree are they susceptible to tinkering and then building the product that they say they want, but also really forcing them to come to terms with if that's really what they want. Because everybody's like, yeah, I'd love to have performance, but I don't want to have performance. And so, I think that's a really good answer. And it's like, all right, well, what if the option was... And again, this is a real exercise. We happen to have two indices that kind of traffic in the same asset class. They're constructed a little bit differently. And so, one of them is going to be down, call it 15... One of them would have been down and call it 15% in 2008, but it also would have been up more than 20% in 2013 when the S&P was up 30%. And so, that's very different, even if it has the same alpha over market cycle as the one that was... Flat in both 2008 and 2013. We've found, like I said, you've written about this a lot. I think it's a really good way to frame the conversation with clients and hopefully very quickly suss out what risk do they really want? Because a large risk for them is the tracking error risk, whether or not they admit it. A lot of people say they're absolutely return focused, but at the end of the day, relative performance matters a lot more and they can justify being down. Less in 2008, a lot easier than they can justify missing out on 2013. But it's tough. I mean, the tinker's dilemma, as you said, is huge and way, candidly, way more prevalent than I would have thought.
